[0m[49m[39m  182, 192[0m:[39m[49m ### Code
[0m[49m[39m  183, 193[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  184, 194[0m:[39m[49m > **Reference implementations:** The following resources demonstrate patterns used in this recipe:
[0m[49m[39m  185, 195[0m:[39m[49m >
[0m[49m[39m  186, 196[0m:[39m[49m > - [MIMIC-IV Clinical Database](https://physionet.org/content/mimiciv/): De-identified ICU data for model development and benchmarking
[0m[49m[39m  187, 197[0m:[39m[49m > - [Amazon SageMaker Examples](https://github.com/aws/amazon-sagemaker-examples): General SageMaker training and deployment patterns
[0m[49m[39m  188, 198[0m:[39m[49m > - [Amazon HealthLake Documentation](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/healthlake/): FHIR data store integration patterns
[0m[49m[39m  189, 199[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  190, 200[0m:[39m[49m #### Walkthrough
[0m[49m[39m  191, 201[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  192, 202[0m:[39m[49m **Step 1: Extract clinical features from FHIR store.** When a prediction is triggered (either by new data arriving or by the scheduled 4-hour refresh), the system queries HealthLake for the patient's current ICU data. This includes vital signs, laboratory results, medications, and clinical assessments from the current admission. The query window matters: we want the full ICU trajectory, not just the most recent values, because temporal patterns (is the patient getting better or worse?) are among the strongest predictors. Skip this step or use stale data, and the prediction reflects yesterday's patient, not today's.
[0m[49m[39m  193, 203[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  194, 204[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  195, 205[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION extract_icu_features(patient_id, admission_id):
[0m[49m[39m  196, 206[0m:[39m[49m     // Query the FHIR store for all relevant observations during this ICU stay.
[0m[49m[39m  197, 207[0m:[39m[49m     // We need vital signs, labs, medications, and assessments.
[0m[49m[39m  198, 208[0m:[39m[49m     // The time window is from ICU admission to now.
[0m[49m[39m  199, 209[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  200, 210[0m:[39m[49m     admission = query HealthLake for Encounter where:
[0m[49m[39m  201, 211[0m:[39m[49m         patient = patient_id
[0m[49m[39m  202, 212[0m:[39m[49m         id = admission_id
[0m[49m[39m  203, 213[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  204, 214[0m:[39m[49m     icu_start = admission.period.start
[0m[49m[39m  205, 215[0m:[39m[49m     now = current UTC timestamp
[0m[49m[39m  206, 216[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  207, 217[0m:[39m[49m     // Vital signs: heart rate, blood pressure, respiratory rate, SpO2, temperature
[0m[49m[39m  208, 218[0m:[39m[49m     vitals = query HealthLake for Observation where:
[0m[49m[39m  209, 219[0m:[39m[49m         patient = patient_id
[0m[49m[39m  210, 220[0m:[39m[49m         category = "vital-signs"
[0m[49m[39m  211, 221[0m:[39m[49m         date >= icu_start
[0m[49m[39m  212, 222[0m:[39m[49m         date <= now
[0m[49m[39m  213, 223[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  214, 224[0m:[39m[49m     // Laboratory results: metabolic panel, CBC, ABG, lactate, coagulation
[0m[49m[39m  215, 225[0m:[39m[49m     labs = query HealthLake for Observation where:
[0m[49m[39m  216, 226[0m:[39m[49m         patient = patient_id
[0m[49m[39m  217, 227[0m:[39m[49m         category = "laboratory"
[0m[49m[39m  218, 228[0m:[39m[49m         date >= icu_start
[0m[49m[39m  219, 229[0m:[39m[49m         date <= now
[0m[49m[39m  220, 230[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  221, 231[0m:[39m[49m     // Active medications: vasopressors, sedatives, antibiotics
[0m[49m[39m  222, 232[0m:[39m[49m     medications = query HealthLake for MedicationAdministration where:
[0m[49m[39m  223, 233[0m:[39m[49m         patient = patient_id
[0m[49m[39m  224, 234[0m:[39m[49m         effective-time >= icu_start
[0m[49m[39m  225, 235[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  226, 236[0m:[39m[49m     // Patient demographics and comorbidities
[0m[49m[39m  227, 237[0m:[39m[49m     patient_info = query HealthLake for Patient where id = patient_id
[0m[49m[39m  228, 238[0m:[39m[49m     conditions = query HealthLake for Condition where:
[0m[49m[39m  229, 239[0m:[39m[49m         patient = patient_id
[0m[49m[39m  230, 240[0m:[39m[49m         clinical-status = "active"
[0m[49m[39m  231, 241[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  232, 242[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN {
[0m[49m[39m  233, 243[0m:[39m[49m         vitals: vitals,
[0m[49m[39m  234, 244[0m:[39m[49m         labs: labs,
[0m[49m[39m  235, 245[0m:[39m[49m         medications: medications,
[0m[49m[39m  236, 246[0m:[39m[49m         patient_info: patient_info,
[0m[49m[39m  237, 247[0m:[39m[49m         conditions: conditions,
[0m[49m[39m  238, 248[0m:[39m[49m         icu_start: icu_start,
[0m[49m[39m  239, 249[0m:[39m[49m         hours_since_admission: (now - icu_start) in hours
[0m[49m[39m  240, 250[0m:[39m[49m     }
[0m[49m[39m  241, 251[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  242, 252[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  243, 253[0m:[39m[49m **Step 2: Engineer temporal features.** Raw clinical data isn't model-ready. A heart rate of 110 means something different if it's been 110 for three days (chronic tachycardia, possibly compensated) versus if it jumped from 70 to 110 in the last hour (acute decompensation). This step transforms raw time-series data into features that capture both current state and trajectory. The feature set includes: worst/best values in multiple time windows, trends (slope over last 6/12/24 hours), variability (coefficient of variation), and derived physiological indices. Missing values are handled explicitly: a missing lactate is informative (either the clinician didn't think it was needed, or the result isn't back yet), not just a gap to fill.
[0m[49m[39m  244, 254[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  245, 255[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  246, 256[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION engineer_features(raw_data):
[0m[49m[39m  247, 257[0m:[39m[49m     features = empty map
[0m[49m[39m  248, 258[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  249, 259[0m:[39m[49m     // Time windows for aggregation: last 6 hours, 12 hours, 24 hours, full stay
[0m[49m[39m  250, 260[0m:[39m[49m     windows = [6, 12, 24, "full_stay"]
[0m[49m[39m  251, 261[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  252, 262[0m:[39m[49m     // For each vital sign, compute summary statistics per window
[0m[49m[39m  253, 263[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each vital_type in ["heart_rate", "sbp", "dbp", "map", "resp_rate", "spo2", "temp"]:
[0m[49m[39m  254, 264[0m:[39m[49m         values = filter raw_data.vitals where code matches vital_type
[0m[49m[39m  255, 265[0m:[39m[49m         
[0m[49m[39m  256, 266[0m:[39m[49m         FOR each window in windows:
[0m[49m[39m  257, 267[0m:[39m[49m             windowed = filter values to last {window} hours
[0m[49m[39m  258, 268[0m:[39m[49m             
[0m[49m[39m  259, 269[0m:[39m[49m             features["{vital_type}_min_{window}h"] = minimum of windowed values
[0m[49m[39m  260, 270[0m:[39m[49m             features["{vital_type}_max_{window}h"] = maximum of windowed values
[0m[49m[39m  261, 271[0m:[39m[49m             features["{vital_type}_mean_{window}h"] = mean of windowed values
[0m[49m[39m  262, 272[0m:[39m[49m             features["{vital_type}_std_{window}h"] = standard deviation of windowed values
[0m[49m[39m  263, 273[0m:[39m[49m             features["{vital_type}_trend_{window}h"] = linear slope of windowed values
[0m[49m[39m  264, 274[0m:[39m[49m             features["{vital_type}_count_{window}h"] = count of observations
[0m[49m[39m  265, 275[0m:[39m[49m                 // count matters: more frequent monitoring = sicker patient
[0m[49m[39m  266, 276[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  267, 277[0m:[39m[49m     // Laboratory features: most recent value, worst in stay, trend
[0m[49m[39m  268, 278[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each lab_type in ["lactate", "creatinine", "bilirubin", "platelets", 
[0m[49m[39m  269, 279[0m:[39m[49m                           "wbc", "hemoglobin", "pao2", "paco2", "ph", "bicarbonate",
[0m[49m[39m  270, 280[0m:[39m[49m                           "sodium", "potassium", "glucose", "inr", "bun"]:
[0m[49m[39m  271, 281[0m:[39m[49m         values = filter raw_data.labs where code matches lab_type
[0m[49m[39m  272, 282[0m:[39m[49m         
[0m[49m[39m  273, 283[0m:[39m[49m         features["{lab_type}_latest"] = most recent value (or NULL if never measured)
[0m[49m[39m  274, 284[0m:[39m[49m         features["{lab_type}_worst"] = worst value during stay
[0m[49m[39m  275, 285[0m:[39m[49m         features["{lab_type}_trend"] = slope of values over stay
[0m[49m[39m  276, 286[0m:[39m[49m         features["{lab_type}_missing"] = 1 if never measured, 0 otherwise
[0m[49m[39m  277, 287[0m:[39m[49m             // explicit missing indicator: absence of a test is informative
[0m[49m[39m  278, 288[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  279, 289[0m:[39m[49m     // Derived physiological indices
[0m[49m[39m  280, 290[0m:[39m[49m     IF features["pao2_latest"] is not NULL AND fio2 is available:
[0m[49m[39m  281, 291[0m:[39m[49m         features["pf_ratio"] = features["pao2_latest"] / fio2
[0m[49m[39m  282, 292[0m:[39m[49m             // P/F ratio: key indicator of respiratory failure severity
[0m[49m[39m  283, 293[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  284, 294[0m:[39m[49m     features["shock_index"] = features["heart_rate_mean_6h"] / features["sbp_mean_6h"]
[0m[49m[39m  285, 295[0m:[39m[49m         // Shock index > 1.0 suggests hemodynamic instability
[0m[49m[39m  286, 296[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  287, 297[0m:[39m[49m     // Vasopressor burden: are they on pressors? How many? What dose?
[0m[49m[39m  288, 298[0m:[39m[49m     active_pressors = filter raw_data.medications where:
[0m[49m[39m  289, 299[0m:[39m[49m         category = "vasopressor" AND status = "active"
[0m[49m[39m  290, 300[0m:[39m[49m     features["vasopressor_count"] = count of active_pressors
[0m[49m[39m  291, 301[0m:[39m[49m     features["norepinephrine_dose"] = max dose of norepinephrine (or 0)
[0m[49m[39m  292, 302[0m:[39m[49m     features["on_vasopressors"] = 1 if vasopressor_count > 0, else 0
[0m[49m[39m  293, 303[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  294, 304[0m:[39m[49m     // Ventilation status
[0m[49m[39m  295, 305[0m:[39m[49m     features["on_mechanical_ventilation"] = 1 if ventilator observations exist in last 6h, else 0
[0m[49m[39m  296, 306[0m:[39m[49m     features["fio2_latest"] = most recent FiO2 value (or 0.21 if not ventilated)
[0m[49m[39m  297, 307[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  298, 308[0m:[39m[49m     // Demographics and admission context
[0m[49m[39m  299, 309[0m:[39m[49m     features["age"] = patient age in years
[0m[49m[39m  300, 310[0m:[39m[49m     features["sex_male"] = 1 if male, 0 otherwise
[0m[49m[39m  301, 311[0m:[39m[49m     features["hours_in_icu"] = raw_data.hours_since_admission
[0m[49m[39m  302, 312[0m:[39m[49m     features["surgical_admission"] = 1 if admission type is surgical, else 0
[0m[49m[39m  303, 313[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  304, 314[0m:[39m[49m     // Comorbidity burden (Charlson-style)
[0m[49m[39m  305, 315[0m:[39m[49m     features["comorbidity_count"] = count of active conditions
[0m[49m[39m  306, 316[0m:[39m[49m     features["has_cancer"] = 1 if any oncology condition, else 0
[0m[49m[39m  307, 317[0m:[39m[49m     features["has_ckd"] = 1 if chronic kidney disease, else 0
[0m[49m[39m  308, 318[0m:[39m[49m     features["has_chf"] = 1 if congestive heart failure, else 0
[0m[49m[39m  309, 319[0m:[39m[49m     features["has_copd"] = 1 if COPD, else 0
[0m[49m[39m  310, 320[0m:[39m[49m     features["has_diabetes"] = 1 if diabetes, else 0
[0m[49m[39m  311, 321[0m:[39m[49m     features["has_liver_disease"] = 1 if cirrhosis or liver failure, else 0
[0m[49m[39m  312, 322[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  313, 323[0m:[39m[49m     // SOFA component scores (computed from raw data, not from EHR-calculated SOFA)
[0m[49m[39m  314, 324[0m:[39m[49m     features["sofa_respiratory"] = compute_sofa_respiratory(features["pf_ratio"])
[0m[49m[39m  315, 325[0m:[39m[49m     features["sofa_coagulation"] = compute_sofa_coagulation(features["platelets_latest"])
[0m[49m[39m  316, 326[0m:[39m[49m     features["sofa_liver"] = compute_sofa_liver(features["bilirubin_latest"])
[0m[49m[39m  317, 327[0m:[39m[49m     features["sofa_cardiovascular"] = compute_sofa_cardiovascular(
[0m[49m[39m  318, 328[0m:[39m[49m         features["map_mean_6h"], features["norepinephrine_dose"])
[0m[49m[39m  319, 329[0m:[39m[49m     features["sofa_cns"] = compute_sofa_cns(gcs_score)
[0m[49m[39m  320, 330[0m:[39m[49m     features["sofa_renal"] = compute_sofa_renal(
[0m[49m[39m  321, 331[0m:[39m[49m         features["creatinine_latest"], urine_output_24h)
[0m[49m[39m  322, 332[0m:[39m[49m     features["sofa_total"] = sum of all SOFA components
[0m[49m[39m  323, 333[0m:[39m[49m     features["sofa_trend_24h"] = sofa_total now minus sofa_total 24 hours ago
[0m[49m[39m  324, 334[0m:[39m[49m         // Rising SOFA = deteriorating. This trend is more predictive than the absolute value.
[0m[49m[39m  325, 335[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  326, 336[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN features
[0m[49m[39m  327, 337[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  328, 338[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 329     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m **Step 3: Score with the mortality model.** The engineered feature vector is sent to the SageMaker endpoint hosting the trained model. The model returns a raw probability score. For gradient boosted trees, this is the output of the sigmoid function applied to the sum of tree predictions. The raw score reflects the training population's mortality rate, which may not match your hospital's population. That's why we don't use this score directly. It goes through calibration in the next step. Skip this step and you have features with no prediction. Use the raw score without calibration and you have a prediction that's relatively correct (ranks patients properly) but absolutely wrong (the probabilities don't mean what they say).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      339[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 3: Score with the mortality model.** The engineered feature vector is sent to the SageMaker endpoint hosting the trained model. The model returns a raw probability score along with SHAP explanations for the prediction. For gradient boosted trees, the raw score is the output of the sigmoid function applied to the sum of tree predictions. The raw score reflects the training population's mortality rate, which may not match your hospital's population. That's why we don't use this score directly. It goes through calibration in the next step. Use the raw score without calibration and you have a prediction that's relatively correct (ranks patients properly) but absolutely wrong (the probabilities don't mean what they say).
[0m[49m[39m  330, 340[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  331, 341[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  332, 342[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION score_patient(features):
[0m[49m[39m  333, 343[0m:[39m[49m     // Format the feature vector for the SageMaker endpoint.
[0m[49m[39m  334, 344[0m:[39m[49m     // The model expects features in a specific order matching the training schema.
[0m[49m[39m  335, 345[0m:[39m[49m     feature_vector = order features according to MODEL_FEATURE_SCHEMA
[0m[49m[39m  336, 346[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  337, 347[0m:[39m[49m     // Handle any remaining missing values with the model's expected sentinel.
[0m[49m[39m  338, 348[0m:[39m[49m     // XGBoost handles NaN natively; other frameworks may need explicit imputation.
[0m[49m[39m  339, 349[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each value in feature_vector:
[0m[49m[39m  340, 350[0m:[39m[49m         IF value is NULL:
[0m[49m[39m  341, 351[0m:[39m[49m             replace with NaN  // XGBoost's native missing value handling
[0m[49m[39m  342, 352[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  343, 353[0m:[39m[49m     // Call the SageMaker real-time inference endpoint.
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 344     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m     // This returns a raw probability from the model's training distribution.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      354[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Production: use a single endpoint call that returns score + explanations
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      355[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // to reduce latency and attack surface. Most XGBoost serving containers
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      356[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // support returning both predictions and SHAP values in one response.
[0m[49m[39m  345, 357[0m:[39m[49m     response = call SageMaker.InvokeEndpoint with:
[0m[49m[39m  346, 358[0m:[39m[49m         endpoint_name = "icu-mortality-model-v2"
[0m[49m[39m  347, 359[0m:[39m[49m         content_type = "text/csv"
[0m[49m[39m  348, 360[0m:[39m[49m         body = feature_vector as CSV row
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      361[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         custom_attributes = "explain=true"
[0m[49m[39m  349, 362[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  350, 363[0m:[39m[49m     raw_score = parse float from response.Body
[0m[49m[39m  351, 364[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 352     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m     // Also extract feature importance for this specific prediction (SHAP values).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      365[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Extract feature importance for this specific prediction (SHAP values).
[0m[49m[39m  353, 366[0m:[39m[49m     // These explain WHY this patient scored high or low.
[0m[49m[39m  354, 367[0m:[39m[49m     // Critical for clinician trust: "the model says 65% because of rising lactate,
[0m[49m[39m  355, 368[0m:[39m[49m     // worsening P/F ratio, and increasing vasopressor requirements."
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 356     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m     shap_response = call SageMaker.InvokeEndpoint with:
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 357     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m         endpoint_name = "icu-mortality-model-v2"
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 358     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m         content_type = "text/csv"
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 359     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m         body = feature_vector as CSV row
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 360     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m         custom_attributes = "explain=true"
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 361     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 362     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m     shap_values = parse SHAP values from shap_response
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      369[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     shap_values = parse SHAP values from response
[0m[49m[39m  363, 370[0m:[39m[49m     top_contributors = select top 5 features by absolute SHAP value
[0m[49m[39m  364, 371[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  365, 372[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN {
[0m[49m[39m  366, 373[0m:[39m[49m         raw_score: raw_score,
[0m[49m[39m  367, 374[0m:[39m[49m         top_contributors: top_contributors
[0m[49m[39m  368, 375[0m:[39m[49m     }
[0m[49m[39m  369, 376[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  370, 377[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  371, 378[0m:[39m[49m **Step 4: Apply local calibration.** The raw model score is transformed through a calibration function trained on your hospital's recent outcomes. This is where the model becomes honest for your population. The calibration function is typically isotonic regression or Platt scaling, fitted on the last 6-12 months of local predictions and outcomes. It's retrained monthly as new outcome data accumulates. Without this step, a model trained on academic medical center data will systematically overestimate mortality at a community hospital (or vice versa). The calibrated score is what gets shown to clinicians.
[0m[49m[39m  372, 379[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  373, 380[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  374, 381[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION calibrate_score(raw_score, hospital_id):
[0m[49m[39m  375, 382[0m:[39m[49m     // Load the hospital-specific calibration function.
[0m[49m[39m  376, 383[0m:[39m[49m     // This was fitted on recent local outcomes and is refreshed monthly.
[0m[49m[39m  377, 384[0m:[39m[49m     calibration_params = load from DynamoDB table "calibration-parameters"
[0m[49m[39m  378, 385[0m:[39m[49m         where hospital = hospital_id AND model_version = current model version
[0m[49m[39m  379, 386[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  380, 387[0m:[39m[49m     // Apply isotonic regression calibration.
[0m[49m[39m  381, 388[0m:[39m[49m     // This maps the raw model output to a probability that's accurate
[0m[49m[39m  382, 389[0m:[39m[49m     // for THIS hospital's patient population.
[0m[49m[39m  383, 390[0m:[39m[49m     calibrated_score = apply_isotonic_regression(raw_score, calibration_params)
[0m[49m[39m  384, 391[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  385, 392[0m:[39m[49m     // Compute confidence interval using the calibration uncertainty.
[0m[49m[39m  386, 393[0m:[39m[49m     // A score based on 10,000 local outcomes has tighter bounds than one based on 500.
[0m[49m[39m  387, 394[0m:[39m[49m     n_calibration_samples = calibration_params.sample_size
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 388     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m     // Wilson score interval for binomial proportion
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      395[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Wilson score interval for binomial proportion.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      396[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // This approximates calibration uncertainty. For more rigorous uncertainty
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      397[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // quantification, consider Bayesian calibration (beta-binomial posterior)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      398[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // or conformal prediction intervals.
[0m[49m[39m  389, 399[0m:[39m[49m     ci_lower, ci_upper = wilson_confidence_interval(
[0m[49m[39m  390, 400[0m:[39m[49m         calibrated_score, n_calibration_samples, confidence=0.95)
[0m[49m[39m  391, 401[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  392, 402[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN {
[0m[49m[39m  393, 403[0m:[39m[49m         mortality_probability: calibrated_score,
[0m[49m[39m  394, 404[0m:[39m[49m         confidence_interval: [ci_lower, ci_upper],
[0m[49m[39m  395, 405[0m:[39m[49m         calibration_date: calibration_params.last_updated,
[0m[49m[39m  396, 406[0m:[39m[49m         calibration_sample_size: n_calibration_samples
[0m[49m[39m  397, 407[0m:[39m[49m     }
[0m[49m[39m  398, 408[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  399, 409[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  400, 410[0m:[39m[49m **Step 5: Store prediction and serve to clinical display.** The calibrated prediction, along with its contributing factors and metadata, is written to DynamoDB for durability and audit. It's simultaneously made available via API Gateway for the clinical dashboard or EHR integration. The stored record includes everything needed for outcome tracking: the prediction, when it was made, what model version produced it, and what the top contributing features were. This enables retrospective analysis of model performance and supports the retraining pipeline. The clinical display shows the probability, the confidence interval, the top contributing factors in plain language, and a clear disclaimer that this is a statistical estimate to inform (not replace) clinical judgment.
[0m[49m[39m  401, 411[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  402, 412[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  403, 413[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION store_and_serve(patient_id, admission_id, calibration_result, model_output):
[0m[49m[39m  404, 414[0m:[39m[49m     prediction_id = generate unique ID
[0m[49m[39m  405, 415[0m:[39m[49m     timestamp = current UTC timestamp (ISO 8601)
[0m[49m[39m  406, 416[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  407, 417[0m:[39m[49m     // Build the complete prediction record for storage and display.
[0m[49m[39m  408, 418[0m:[39m[49m     prediction_record = {
[0m[49m[39m  409, 419[0m:[39m[49m         prediction_id: prediction_id,
[0m[49m[39m  410, 420[0m:[39m[49m         patient_id: patient_id,
[0m[49m[39m  411, 421[0m:[39m[49m         admission_id: admission_id,
[0m[49m[39m  412, 422[0m:[39m[49m         timestamp: timestamp,
[0m[49m[39m  413, 423[0m:[39m[49m         model_version: "icu-mortality-v2.3",
[0m[49m[39m  414, 424[0m:[39m[49m         
[0m[49m[39m  415, 425[0m:[39m[49m         // The prediction itself
[0m[49m[39m  416, 426[0m:[39m[49m         mortality_probability: calibration_result.mortality_probability,
[0m[49m[39m  417, 427[0m:[39m[49m         confidence_interval: calibration_result.confidence_interval,
[0m[49m[39m  418, 428[0m:[39m[49m         raw_model_score: model_output.raw_score,
[0m[49m[39m  419, 429[0m:[39m[49m         
[0m[49m[39m  420, 430[0m:[39m[49m         // Explainability: why this score?
[0m[49m[39m  421, 431[0m:[39m[49m         top_contributors: model_output.top_contributors,
[0m[49m[39m  422, 432[0m:[39m[49m         // Example: [{"feature": "sofa_trend_24h", "direction": "increasing", 
[0m[49m[39m  423, 433[0m:[39m[49m         //            "contribution": 0.12, "plain_text": "Organ failure worsening over 24h"},
[0m[49m[39m  424, 434[0m:[39m[49m         //           {"feature": "lactate_latest", "direction": "high",
[0m[49m[39m  425, 435[0m:[39m[49m         //            "contribution": 0.09, "plain_text": "Elevated lactate (4.2 mmol/L)"}]
[0m[49m[39m  426, 436[0m:[39m[49m         
[0m[49m[39m  427, 437[0m:[39m[49m         // Metadata for audit and monitoring
[0m[49m[39m  428, 438[0m:[39m[49m         calibration_date: calibration_result.calibration_date,
[0m[49m[39m  429, 439[0m:[39m[49m         hours_since_admission: features.hours_in_icu,
[0m[49m[39m  430, 440[0m:[39m[49m         
[0m[49m[39m  431, 441[0m:[39m[49m         // Outcome tracking (filled in later)
[0m[49m[39m  432, 442[0m:[39m[49m         actual_outcome: NULL,  // populated when patient is discharged or dies
[0m[49m[39m  433, 443[0m:[39m[49m         goals_of_care_changed: NULL  // tracked for self-fulfilling prophecy monitoring
[0m[49m[39m  434, 444[0m:[39m[49m     }
[0m[49m[39m  435, 445[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  436, 446[0m:[39m[49m     // Write to DynamoDB with the prediction_id as partition key
[0m[49m[39m  437, 447[0m:[39m[49m     // and patient_id + timestamp as a GSI for patient-level queries.
[0m[49m[39m  438, 448[0m:[39m[49m     write prediction_record to DynamoDB table "icu-mortality-predictions"
[0m[49m[39m  439, 449[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  440, 450[0m:[39m[49m     // Publish a custom CloudWatch metric for monitoring prediction distribution.
[0m[49m[39m  441, 451[0m:[39m[49m     // If the average predicted mortality suddenly shifts, something changed
[0m[49m[39m  442, 452[0m:[39m[49m     // (patient population, data pipeline, or model drift).
[0m[49m[39m  443, 453[0m:[39m[49m     publish CloudWatch metric:
[0m[49m[39m  444, 454[0m:[39m[49m         namespace = "ICU/MortalityModel"
[0m[49m[39m  445, 455[0m:[39m[49m         metric_name = "PredictedMortality"
[0m[49m[39m  446, 456[0m:[39m[49m         value = calibration_result.mortality_probability
[0m[49m[39m  447, 457[0m:[39m[49m         dimensions = { hospital_id, model_version }
[0m[49m[39m  448, 458[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  449, 459[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN prediction_record
[0m[49m[39m  450, 460[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  451, 461[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  452, 462[0m:[39m[49m > **Curious how this looks in Python?** The pseudocode above covers the concepts. If you'd like to see sample Python code that demonstrates these patterns using boto3, check out the [Python Example](chapter07.09-python-example). It walks through each step with inline comments and notes on what you'd need to change for a real deployment.
